body:
“Teasing” A Brie Larson imagine

Note: y/s/n= your sisters name

After dating Brie for two years the time finally came for her to meet your family. She had been asking for a while to meet your family, but you were hesitant because your family was very odd and you were afraid they would scare her off. So, instead of meeting all your family members at once, you decided to introduce them one by one. You started out with your older sister.

“Why are you so nervous?” Brie asked from the kitchen. She was still in the process of making lunch for the three of you. You stood in the living room looking out the window, waiting for your sister.

“Because, she’s my older sister and she judges every aspect of my life. I also want to impress her.”

“Babe, I’m sure it’ll be fine.” Right after Brie finished her sentence, a black car pulled up in front of your home.

“Speak of the devil.” You went outside to help her with her excessive amount of bags for a three day stay.

“Hey y/n!”

“Hey sis! How was the flight?” You bent down and tried to pick up three of her five bags.

“It was great. No one was sitting beside me and there were no crying babies.”

“Wow that is great.”

“Yes it is. So, is this your home or your girlfriend’s? Mom wants to know.”

“It’s hers. We decided it would be best if I moved in instead of trying to find a new house. Why does she want to know?”

“You know how nosy mom is. She knows everyone’s business in the neighborhood.”

Your sister didn’t say anything else but continued to look the house over. With straining arms, you lead her inside your home. You were surprised to see Brie standing by the couch when the two of you walked in.

“Y/s/n, it’s nice to finally meet you!”

“It’s nice to finally meet you!” You stood in shock as the women hugged. Yes, Brie was a hugger but your sister, she would rather jump off a bridge than be hugged by a stranger.

“You two are oddly happy to see each other.”

“Well yeah, we’ve been talking for months about this.” Your sister said as she pulled away from Brie’s hug. You have Brie a confused look because she usually told you about the people she talked to.

“You have?”

“Yeah! I thought you were never going to let me meet Brie, so I started talking to her on Instagram a few months ago.”

“You guys have been talking behind my back this whole time?”

“Not necessarily talking behind your back. More like getting to know each other and exchanging embarrassing stories about you. My personal favorite was when you put sunblock on your-“

“Brie, you told her that story?!”

“We were talking about family vacations and I told her about ours in Italy.” She said with tight shoulders and not sounding sorry at all.

“It’s alright, y/n. At least I didn’t tell her about the time you tried to jump our backyard fence, ripped your pants, set off the security alarm, and had to have mom help you down.”

“Babe, did you seriously do that?”

“I don’t want to talk about it. Let’s have lunch instead, y/s/n must be hungry from the long flight.”

You stormed past your girlfriend and sister to get to the kitchen. Brie and y/s/n sat at the dining room table and made small talk. You carried the salad Brie made into the dining room and noticed they were smirking at you.

“What did you say now?”

“I was telling Brie about how clumsy you were as a teenager. Remember when you worked at that restaurant and dumped an entire tray of food on a table?”

“That wasn’t my fault. One of the women left their purses on the floor and a tripped.”

“It was bad, Brie. There was mashed potatoes everywhere.” The girls were giggling, making you feel embarrassed about your teenage years. With a sigh, you sat down and started eating.

Thankfully, as lunch and the rest of the day went on, your sister and Brie let up on the teasing. The three of you were even able to go out shopping without any fights or snarky comments, something you and your sister could rarely accomplish. You were in a partially empty designer store when Brie got a call from her manager. She quickly excused herself, leaving you and your sister alone.

“I like Brie. She’s nice and she’s good to you.” Your sister suddenly said.

“I’m glad you like her. Brie’s all about being close with family. I’m probably going to have to fly mom out soon to meet her.”

“Do you think you’ll get married?”

“I would like to, but I don’t know if Brie does.” That caused your sister to stop dead in her tracks. You turned around with a questioning look.

“Are you kidding me? Brie is so in love with you, of course she wants to marry you.”

“You really think so?”

“I know so. She looks at you like you’re the only person in the room. If you want, I’ll go with you ring shopping.” The mention of rings made your breath hitch. Sure, you had thrown around the idea of getting married, but it was never very serious.

“Maybe in a few years. I think Brie and I are in a really good place right now.”

“Okay, if you change your mind I will gladly get on a plane and come here.” It brought a genuine smile to your face to know your sister wanted to be part of a huge moment of your life.

“Thank you. I’ll remember that.” You cautiously wrapped your sister in a hug. Her arms wrapped around you and she let out a content sigh.

“Okay, now that we’ve had our one sappy sibling moment for the year, let’s go grab Brie. I want you guys to show me more parts of the city.” You pulled away from the hug with a laugh.

“Alright, just don’t get your hopes up. Not every place can be as nice as Rodeo Drive.”

Your sister rolled her eyes at you before walking towards the store’s front door. You followed close behind, hoping y/s/n and Brie wouldn’t start the teasing again.
